## 8. Drift Detection Protocol

Drift is not minor. Drift is one of the main failure modes of the repository.

You must actively detect and report drift in every review.

### 8.1 Structural Drift
- same responsibility implemented differently in different spaces
- multiple execution paths for one platform behavior
- feature-specific exceptions added instead of shared logic

### 8.2 Naming Drift
- approved product language replaced with synonyms
- old terms reappear
- inconsistent capitalization or product naming

### 8.3 Billing Drift
- multiple entitlement checks with different logic
- gate behavior differs by space without documented reason
- frontend assumptions diverge from backend truth

### 8.4 UI Drift
- shell structure differs across spaces without product reason
- inconsistent border/corner/palette behavior
- mixed design systems begin to appear

### 8.5 Data Drift
- more than one source of truth for the same concept
- schema changes without platform-wide wiring
- save paths diverge by space unnecessarily

### 8.6 Prompt and AI Drift
- one route uses different behavioral language standards
- hidden prompt forks contradict product voice or safety posture
- output shape varies without documented reason

If drift is found, return `FAIL` unless the change explicitly fixes the drift.

