## 14. Practical Review Heuristics

Use the following heuristics when reviewing implementation quality.

### 14.1 Good Changes Usually:
- centralize logic instead of scattering it,
- reuse shared patterns,
- align naming with product vocabulary,
- make saved state more real and durable,
- strengthen server-side truth,
- improve clarity without adding system complexity.

### 14.2 Bad Changes Usually:
- solve only the local problem,
- introduce one-off exceptions,
- copy logic between spaces,
- put sensitive logic in the client,
- use temporary naming or placeholder language,
- create feature behavior that the rest of the platform does not understand.

